line or in writing by post.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "4. Pay for application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "There is a fee for this application. To find out how much your application costs, visit our web page Fees: costs of an application.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You pay the fees when you collect the residence permit.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "5. Wait for decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The IND must take a decision within 8 weeks. This is called the decision period.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "We can extend the decision period if it takes longer to decide. For example, because the application is not complete. In that case, the IND will send a message.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Replacement of an asylum residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Is your residence permit in the process of being replaced and because of this you no longer have a valid proof of identity? In this case, you can apply for a Foreign National''s Identity Document.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Follow the application in My IND.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "6. Decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The decision is written in a letter. The decision will be positive or negative.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Positive decision: you will receive a new residence permit.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Negative decision: you will not receive a new residence permit. You can object against this decision.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "7. Collect residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "When the residence permit is ready at an IND desk, you will receive a letter. You must make an appointment to collect your residence document.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "The new residence permit usually has the same end date as the permit you replaced. Was the permit you replaced only still valid for less than 1 month? Then you will not receive a new residence permit, but a letter. This letter states until when you have a right of residence in the Netherlands.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Application forms", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You can submit this application online. You must have DigiD with SMS verification and internet banking (iDEAL).Is your residence permit valid for less than 3 months? In that case you can only submit the written application form.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Online application form replacement", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Apply online You need a DigiD", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Written application forms", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Download the form if you prefer to complete the application in writing and send it by post.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Application replacement or renewal of a foreign nationals document 6013 (PDF, 270.98 KB)", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Residence permit lost or stolen", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Requirements", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Process and costs", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Application forms", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "NarrativeText"}], "fetch_date": "2026-03-02"}', 'webpage', '2026-03-28 16:32:08.725204+00', '2026-03-28 16:25:32.85229+00', 'Residence permit damaged or change of personal details

Last update: 25 January 2024

Is your residence permit, residence document, statelessness document or Foreign Nationals Identity Document damaged? Does it have the wrong personal details? Or do you want to have your employment rights changed? Find out how you can apply for a new residence permit.

Requirements

Process and costs

Application forms

See also

Requirements

Check which requirements apply to you in each situation.

Damaged residence permit

Your residence permit is so damaged that it can no longer be used as a valid proof of identity. Enclose a copy of the front and back of the damaged residence permit with your application for a replacement.

Wrong personal details on residence permit

Contact your local council. They will check whether your personal details are correct in the Personal Records Database (in Dutch: Basisregistratie Personen or BRP). If your personal details in the BRP are incorrect, then the council must first change them. Once they have been changed, you can ask the IND to replace your residence permit.

Changing employment rights on residence permit

You have accrued employment rights and you may now work without a work permit. (In Dutch a work permit is called a tewerkstellingsvergunning or TWV). You can apply for a new residence document on which the following employment rights are written in Dutch: Arbeid vrij toegestaan, TWV niet vereist (Free to work. Work permit not required). This application is free of charge.

It is not possible to change employment rights on a Foreign Nationals Identity Document.

Validity of residence permit less than 1 month

Is your residence permit valid for less than 1 month? Use the following form to apply to extend your residence permit:

Application for extension of residence permit for work related purposes of residence (foreign national) 7535 (PDF, 456.07 KB)

Write on the form that you want to have the employment status arbeid vrij toegestaan (free to work) on your new residence permit. You must pay a fee to apply to have your permit extended.

Process and costs

The process for applying for the residence permit consists of these steps:

Show details Hide details

1. Check requirements

A valid provisional residence permit (MVV) is needed for this application

Make sure you meet the requirements.

1. Check requirements

Make sure you meet the requirements.

2. Collect documents

The written application form lists which documents you need. Collect all documents before you apply. You can upload the documents with the online application.

3. Apply

You can submit this application online or in writing by post.

4. Pay for application

There is a fee for this application. To find out how much your application costs, visit our web page Fees: costs of an application.

You pay the fees when you collect the residence permit.

5. Wait for decision on application

The IND must take a decision within 8 weeks. This is called the decision period.

We can extend the decision period if it takes longer to decide. For example, because the application is not complete. In that case, the IND will send a message.

Replacement of an asylum residence permit

Is your residence permit in the process of being replaced and because of this you no longer have a valid proof of identity? In this case, you can apply for a Foreign National''s Identity Document.

Follow the application in My IND.

6. Decision on application

The decision is written in a letter. The decision will be positive or negative.

Positive decision: you will receive a new residence permit.

Negative decision: you will not receive a new residence permit. You can object against this decision.

7. Collect residence permit

When the residence permit is ready at an IND desk, you will receive a letter. You must make an appointment to collect your residence document.

The new residence permit usually has the same end date as the permit you replaced. Was the permit you replaced only still valid for less than 1 month? Then you will not receive a new residence permit, but a letter. This letter states until when you have a right of residence in the Netherlands.

Application forms

You can submit this application online. You must have DigiD with SMS verification and internet banking (iDEAL).Is your residence permit valid for less than 3 months? In that case you can only submit the written application form.

Online application form replacement

Apply online You need a DigiD

Written application forms

Download the form if you prefer to complete the application in writing and send it by post.

Application replacement or renewal of a foreign nationals document 6013 (PDF, 270.98 KB)

See also

Residence permit lost or stolen

Requirements

Process and costs

Application forms

See also'),
	('6734c3a5-aad6-4977-8724-3383e515387a', 'Dutch citizen by birth, acknowledgment or adoption', 'https://ind.nl/en/dutch-citizenship/dutch-citizen-by-birth-acknowledgment-or-adoption', '{"category": "dutch-citizenship", "elements": [{"text": "Dutch citizen by birth, acknowledgment or adoption", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Last update: 31 December 2025", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "A child can automatically become a Dutch citizen by birth, acknowledgement or adoption. This is also called getting Dutch citizenship by descent. It happens ‘by (operation of) law’. Then you do not have to apply for Dutch nationality. Find out the situations in which your child will automatically get Dutch nationality.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Dutch citizen by birth", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Acknowledgement by a Dutch citizen", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Adoption by a Dutch parent", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Applying for a Dutch passport", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Dutch citizen by birth", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Was your child born after 31 December 1984? In that case your child will automatically get Dutch nationality by birth in these situations:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "The child’s mother had Dutch nationality at the time of the child’s birth.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Both of the child’s parents had Dutch nationality at the time of their child’s birth.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "The child’s father had Dutch nationality at the time of the child’s birth and is married to the child’s non-Dutch mother. Or the father is the mother’s registered partner. Or the father acknowledged the child before the child was born.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "At the time of birth, the child and the child’s mother had their principal residence in the Kingdom of the Netherlands. One of the mother’s parents also had their principal residence in the Kingdom on the day the mother was born.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "The child and the child’s father had their principal residence in the Kingdom of the Netherlands at the time of the child’s birth. One of the father’s parents also had their principal residence in the Kingdom on the day the father was born.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "It makes no difference whether the child was born in the Netherlands or abroad.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Child born before 1 January 1985", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Was the father a Dutch citizen at the time of the child’s birth? In that case the child is also automatically a Dutch citizen by descent. It makes no difference whether the child was born in the Netherlands or abroad.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "What if the mother was a Dutch citizen at the time of the child''s birth, but the father was not? Then the child will not automatically be a Dutch citizen. The child can become a Dutch citizen through option.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Acknowledgement by a Dutch citizen", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Did a Dutch citizen acknowledge the child after 1 March 2009? And did the acknowledging parent do this after the child’s birth and before the child turned 7 years old? In that case the child is automatically a Dutch citizen.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Acknowledgement of a child aged 7 or more", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Was the child 7 years old or more, but under 18, when they were acknowledged? Then the acknowledger must take a DNA test to prove to be the biological parent. An accredited laboratory must perform this test This must be done within 1 year after acknowledgement of the child. If the acknowledger is unable or unwilling to take a DNA test, the child can become a Dutch citizen through option. The acknowledger must also have cared for and brought up the child for at least 3 years without interruption. And the child must be under 18 years old at the time of the application.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Scheme for children acknowledged between 1 April 2003 and 1 March 2009", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "From 1 April 2003 to 1 March 2009 a child could not become a Dutch citizen by acknowledgement. There is a separate scheme for children acknowledged in this period. This scheme also applies to children who have since turned 18 or more. For more information, contact the local council or Dutch representation (embassy or consulate).", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Adoption by a Dutch parent", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Children automatically get Dutch nationality by adoption if they meet the following requirements:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "The child is under 18 years old.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "One of the adoptive parents is a Dutch national.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "The adoption happened under the rules of the Hague Adoption Convention or Book 10 of the Dutch Civil Code (in Dutch: Burgelijk Wetboek or BW).", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "The legal and other family ties with the original parents have been completely broken.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Applying for a Dutch passport", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Is your child automatically a Dutch citizen by law? Then you can apply to your local council for a passport or identity card.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Does your child live abroad? Then apply to the Dutch representation (embassy or consulate) abroad for the passport or identity card.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Visit Netherlandsworldwide.nl for information about applying for a passport or identity card if you live abroad.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Losing Dutch nationality", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Dual nationality through birth (Government.nl) (only available in Dutch)", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Have I lost my nationality?", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "U wordt Nederlander. Wat mag en moet u doen? 6075 (PDF, 197.74 KB)", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "(only available in Dutch)", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Dutch citizen by birth", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Acknowledgement by a Dutch citizen", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Adoption by a Dutch parent", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Applying for a Dutch passport", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "NarrativeText"}], "fetch_date": "2026-03-02"}', 'webpage', '2026-03-28 16:32:08.725204+00', '2026-03-28 16:25:32.85229+00', 'Dutch citizen by birth, acknowledgment or adoption

Last update: 31 December 2025

A child can automatically become a Dutch citizen by birth, acknowledgement or adoption. This is also called getting Dutch citizenship by descent. It happens ‘by (operation of) law’. Then you do not have to apply for Dutch nationality. Find out the situations in which your child will automatically get Dutch nationality.

Dutch citizen by birth

Acknowledgement by a Dutch citizen

Adoption by a Dutch parent

Applying for a Dutch passport

See also

Dutch citizen by birth

Was your child born after 31 December 1984? In that case your child will automatically get Dutch nationality by birth in these situations:

The child’s mother had Dutch nationality at the time of the child’s birth.

Both of the child’s parents had Dutch nationality at the time of their child’s birth.

The child’s father had Dutch nationality at the time of the child’s birth and is married to the child’s non-Dutch mother. Or the father is the mother’s registered partner. Or the father acknowledged the child before the child was born.

At the time of birth, the child and the child’s mother had their principal residence in the Kingdom of the Netherlands. One of the mother’s parents also had their principal residence in the Kingdom on the day the mother was born.

The child and the child’s father had their principal residence in the Kingdom of the Netherlands at the time of the child’s birth. One of the father’s parents also had their principal residence in the Kingdom on the day the father was born.

It makes no difference whether the child was born in the Netherlands or abroad.

Child born before 1 January 1985

Was the father a Dutch citizen at the time of the child’s birth? In that case the child is also automatically a Dutch citizen by descent. It makes no difference whether the child was born in the Netherlands or abroad.

What if the mother was a Dutch citizen at the time of the child''s birth, but the father was not? Then the child will not automatically be a Dutch citizen. The child can become a Dutch citizen through option.

Acknowledgement by a Dutch citizen

Did a Dutch citizen acknowledge the child after 1 March 2009? And did the acknowledging parent do this after the child’s birth and before the child turned 7 years old? In that case the child is automatically a Dutch citizen.

Acknowledgement of a child aged 7 or more

Was the child 7 years old or more, but under 18, when they were acknowledged? Then the acknowledger must take a DNA test to prove to be the biological parent. An accredited laboratory must perform this test This must be done within 1 year after acknowledgement of the child. If the acknowledger is unable or unwilling to take a DNA test, the child can become a Dutch citizen through option. The acknowledger must also have cared for and brought up the child for at least 3 years without interruption. And the child must be under 18 years old at the time of the application.

Scheme for children acknowledged between 1 April 2003 and 1 March 2009

From 1 April 2003 to 1 March 2009 a child could not become a Dutch citizen by acknowledgement. There is a separate scheme for children acknowledged in this period. This scheme also applies to children who have since turned 18 or more. For more information, contact the local council or Dutch representation (embassy or consulate).

Adoption by a Dutch parent

Children automatically get Dutch nationality by adoption if they meet the following requirements:

The child is under 18 years old.

One of the adoptive parents is a Dutch national.

The adoption happened under the rules of the Hague Adoption Convention or Book 10 of the Dutch Civil Code (in Dutch: Burgelijk Wetboek or BW).

The legal and other family ties with the original parents have been completely broken.

Applying for a Dutch passport

Is your child automatically a Dutch citizen by law? Then you can apply to your local council for a passport or identity card.

Does your child live abroad? Then apply to the Dutch representation (embassy or consulate) abroad for the passport or identity card.

Visit Netherlandsworldwide.nl for information about applying for a passport or identity card if you live abroad.

See also

Losing Dutch nationality

Dual nationality through birth (Government.nl) (only available in Dutch)

Have I lost my nationality?

U wordt Nederlander. Wat mag en moet u doen? 6075 (PDF, 197.74 KB)

(only available in Dutch)

Dutch citizen by birth

Acknowledgement by a Dutch citizen

Adoption by a Dutch parent

Applying for a Dutch passport

See also'),
	('d7566411-d9f5-449b-b772-59b2e5ce05ce', 'Becoming a Dutch national through naturalisation', 'https://ind.nl/en/dutch-citizenship/becoming-a-dutch-national-through-naturalisation', '{"category": "dutch-citizenship", "elements": [{"text": "Becoming a Dutch national through naturalisation", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Last update: 28 January 2026", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "You want to apply for Dutch nationality through naturalisation. Watch the video, read the requirements and how to apply for naturalisation.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Video: How can I become Dutch through naturalisation?", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Requirements", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Process and costs", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "After the positive decision", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Video: How can I become Dutch through naturalisation?", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You apply for Dutch nationality with a request for naturalisation. You must submit your application for naturalisation to the municipality. First, watch the video below.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "00:00", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "00:00", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Becoming a Dutch national by means of an option application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Sometimes you can also become a Dutch national in a faster and easier way. We call this option. Different requirements apply for option than for naturalisation. There are a number of advantages:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "For an option application, you usually do not have to renounce your nationality.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "When applying for option, you do not have to demonstrate that you are sufficiently integrated in the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "The costs are lower than for naturalisation.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Check if you are eligible to apply for Dutch nationality by means of an option application.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Requirements", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The following requirements apply to naturalisation:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You must be 18 years or older.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You can prove your identity and nationality with valid documents.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have lived in the Kingdom of the Netherlands for at least 5 consecutive years with a valid residence permit. You have always applied for an extension of your residence permit on time. In some cases you can apply for naturalisation earlier. Find out about exceptions to the 5-year term.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "At the time of your application for naturalisation, you have one of the following residence permits:", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "An asylum permanent residence permit or regular permanent residence permit.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A residence permit as a long-term EU resident.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A temporary residence permit with a non-temporary purpose of stay.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A resident permit as a family member of an EU national (including stay with minor Dutch child, ruling Chavez-Vilchez).", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have residence pursuant to EU law because you have the nationality of an EU or EEA country or Switzerland. You do not need to have a residence permit.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A residence document Article 50 TEU Withdrawal Agreement Brexit (in Dutch: Terugtrekkingsakkoord Brexit) for UK nationals and their family members.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "On the date of the naturalisation ceremony, your residence permit is still valid or you still have a valid right of residence under EU law. Does your residence permit expire during the procedure? Then apply for extension.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have fulfilled the integration requirement. This means you must have passed the civic integration exam on at least language level A2. Sometimes you are exempted from the civic integration exam. For example, because you can already read, write, speak and understand Dutch to a sufficient level. For more information about the civic integration requirement, go to our webpage Civic integration for more secure residence permit and naturalisation.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You are not a danger to the public order or national security of the Kingdom of the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You must renounce your current nationality. There are exemptions to this rule. Find out if you are required to renounce your nationality and what that means for you before you request naturalisation.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You must be willing to make the declaration of solidarity during the naturalisation ceremony. You hereby declare that you are aware that the laws of the Kingdom of the Netherlands also apply to you.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You must have your name determined if your name does not consist of a first name and a last name (surname). Your first name and surname will then be determined together with you.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Naturalisation abroad: no residence permit, but conditions are required", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Are you applying from abroad? Then you do not need a Dutch residence permit. You must meet the requirements that apply to a residence permit for a non-temporary purpose.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Show details Hide details", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Requirements minor children", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "A child under the age of 18 cannot apply for naturalisation themselves. However, you and your child can apply for Dutch nationality together. You will include the naturalisation for your child with your own application (in Dutch: mee-naturalisatie).", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Requirements for including children under the age of 16 in your application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Your child lives in the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your child has a valid permanent residence permit. Or a temporary residence permit with a non-temporary purpose of stay. The residence permit must be valid until the day of the naturalisation ceremony.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Children aged 12 and above must be present when you submit your application to the municipality. Your child will then tell the official what they think of being included in the application for naturalisation.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Requirements for including children aged 16 or 17 years old in your application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Your child has lived in the Netherlands for at least 3 years in a row.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your child has a valid permanent residence permit. Or a temporary residence permit with a non-temporary purpose of stay. The residence permit must be valid until the day of the naturalisation ceremony.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your child must be present when you submit your application to the municipality. Your child must indicate that they agree to being included in the application for naturalisation.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your child must be willing to make the declaration of solidarity during the naturalisation ceremony.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Are you having the name of your child determined or changed? Then your child has to give permission.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Consent of the other parent", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Is only one parent applying for naturalisation? And does this parent also include a child in their application for naturalisation? The other parent must be present at the municipality to give consent to the naturalisation of the child together with the other parent.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Later naturalisation of a child", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Did your child not naturalise together with you? After you have become a Dutch citizen yourself, you can also apply for naturalisation of your child. This is called subsequent naturalisation.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Later naturalisation of an adult child", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Did your child reach the age of majority during your naturalisation or option procedure? And was the child''s application rejected for this reason? If so, then your child can apply for subsequent naturalisation.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Process and costs", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "These are the steps in the application process for the residence permit.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Show details Hide details", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "1. Check requirements", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "A valid provisional residence permit (MVV) is needed for this application", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Make sure you meet the requirements.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "1. Check requirements", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Make sure you meet the requirements.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "2. Collect documents", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You use documents to show that you meet the requirements for naturalisation. Have official foreign documents legalised and translated into Dutch, English, French or German. Are your foreign documents already registered in the Municipal Personal Records Database (BRP)? Then you do not need to obtain and legalise these documents again.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You will need the following documents:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "A valid passport or other travel document.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A birth certificate from your country of origin.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A valid residence permit or other proof of lawful residence. If you are a national of a country in the EU/EEA or Switzerland, you do not need to have a residence permit. The municipality will consult the Personal Records Database (in Dutch: Basisregistratie Personen or BRP) to check how long you have lived in the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A civic integration diploma or other proof of civic integration. Or a certificate of exemption (or partial exemption) from the integration requirement.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Extra documents", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "In some situations, you will need extra documents.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "In case a child under the age of 18 is included in the application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "A valid passport or other travel document, a birth certificate and a residence permit.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A declaration of consent when only parent applies for naturalisation. The other parent must be present at the municipality to declare that they consent to the child being included in the other parent’s application. The other parent must also hand over a copy of their residence permit.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "In case of a 3-year marriage or registered partnership", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "A marriage certificate or certificate of registered partnership. This document is not required if your marriage or partnership is registered in the Personal Records Database (BRP).", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "In case of you lived together abroad", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Documents that prove you lived together abroad. This can be proof of registration in the population register. Can you not obtain this? Then you may also provide, for example, a rental contract or bank statements. These documents must list both your names and the address where you lived together.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "No passport or birth certificate", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you not have a passport or birth certificate? Then you can obtain one by applying to the government of your country of origin. Are you unable to obtain a passport or birth certificate? Then you may be granted an exemption due to lack of documentary evidence.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Doubt about identity and nationality", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "If you want to become a Dutch citizen you have to prove your identity and nationality. If doubt exists about the personal data or nationality you provided, your request may be rejected.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Does the IND doubt the identity or nationality caused by incorrect statements given by your parent(s)? Then the IND will not reject the request. Then the IND will use the identification and nationality that were provided when the minor child received the residence permit.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "3. Apply", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You must submit your application for naturalisation to the municipality where you live. An employee of the municipality will discuss all the requirements with you and check whether you have all the required documents. If something is missing or you need to look into a particular matter, the municipality will make another appointment for you.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Completing the application form", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You will fill in the application form together with a staff member from the municipality. You will also complete the following declarations:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "A declaration of willingness to make the declaration of solidarity. By completing this declaration, you declare that you know that the laws of the Kingdom of the Netherlands also apply to you.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "A declaration of willingness that you will renounce your current nationality if you have become Dutch. Do you not have to renounce because you fall under an exception? Then you indicate this in the declaration.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Including your children in your application for naturalisation", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "If you have children under the age of 18 and you wish to include them in your application for naturalisation, please mention this at the time of the appointment. Your children will then be included in the application. Children aged 12 and above must accompany you on your visit to the municipality to make the application. Your children will then tell the official what they think about the naturalisation. If your children are aged 16 or 17, they must also indicate that they agree to becoming Dutch nationals. Did your child not naturalise together with you? After you have become a Dutch citizen yourself, you can also apply for naturalisation of your child. This is called subsequent naturalisation.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Establishing your name", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Your name may need to be formally established. This means that your first name and last name will be determined together with you. Establishing your name is mandatory if you do not have a first name or last name. This is true if you have 1 name. Or if you have more names without separation between first names and surname. You fill in a form which first name and last name (surname, in Dutch geslachtsnaam) you would like. Are you unsure whether your name should be established? Your municipality can give you more information.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Changing your name", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You may ask to change your surname in your naturalisation application. Or your surname and first name. You can change your name if it is important for your integration. This is only the case in the following situations:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Your name is difficult to pronounce for Dutch people.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have acquired your husband’s surname through marriage and you wish to change that name to your maiden name.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your name is ridiculous according to the general Dutch opinion. This means that your name has an inappropriate meaning in Dutch.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your last name is inflected with a masculine or feminine conjugation. You can then change your last name to the uninflected name. For example, a change from Bonova to Bonov.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have a compound last name, i.e. the name of your mother and your father. One of those names can then become your last name.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Determining or changing names of children", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Children aged 12 to 15 who participate in naturalisation may say what they think about the adoption or change of their name. Children aged 16 or 17 must give permission for their name to be determined or changed.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Send application form", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Once all information has been collected, a municipal employee will prepare advice for the IND. The municipality will then send your application form with all documents and advice to the IND. The IND will decide on your request for naturalisation.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "4. Pay for application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You have to pay for the application. To find out how much your application costs, visit our web page Fees: costs of an application.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You pay the costs (fees) to the municipality when you submit your application.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "5. Wait for decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The IND must take a decision within 12 months. This is called the decision period. You will receive a letter stating the date by which the IND will decide on the application. The decision period begins as soon as the fees for the application have been paid. We can extend the decision period if it takes longer to decide. For example, because the application is not complete. In that case, the IND will send a message.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Follow the application in My IND.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "What if the IND decides late", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Has the decision period passed? And do you still not have a decision on your application? Find out what you can do if the IND is late with its decision.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "6. Decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You will receive the decision in a letter. The decision will be positive or negative.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Positive decision: the IND has given its approval to you becoming a Dutch national. However, this letter does not make you a Dutch national immediately. Find out what you still need to do to become a Dutch national.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Negative decision: you will not obtain Dutch nationality. You can object against this decision.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "After the positive decision", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You have received a positive decision on your application. Find out what else you need to do before you become a Dutch citizen.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Signing of the Royal Decree Dutch Citizenship", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "According to the IND, you meet all requirements to become a Dutch citizen. The IND will forward this decision to the King of the Netherlands. The King needs to place his signature. By signing, the King gives official permission to grant you Dutch nationality. This is called a Royal Decree.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Obligatory participation in naturalisation ceremony", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You will only become a Dutch citizen after you have gone to the required naturalisation ceremony. Do this within 1 year after you’ve received the positive decision. If you do not go, you will not get the Dutch nationality, and you will have to apply for naturalisation again.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Local councils (in Dutch: gemeenten) organise naturalisation ceremonies. The local council celebrates together with you that you have become a Dutch citizen. The naturalisation ceremony also pays special attention to the meaning of Dutch nationality.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Children aged 16 and over", "type": "Title"}, {"text"