ils", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "1. Check requirements", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "A valid provisional residence permit (MVV) is needed for this application", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Make sure you meet the requirements.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "1. Check requirements", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Make sure you meet the requirements.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "2. Collect documents", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The written application form lists which documents you need. This form is only available in English. Collect all documents before you submit the application.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Have official foreign documents legalised and translated into Dutch, English, French or German.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Japan and South Korea: extra documents", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you have the nationality of Japan or South Korea? Then you also need a valid proof of pre-registration. This is an email from the IND. Read how to apply for the pre-registration in step 3.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "3. Apply", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The application process depends on your nationality. Choose the country of your nationality and find out how to apply.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong and Taiwan", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Japan and South Korea", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Australia, New Zealand and Canada", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong and Taiwan", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you have the nationality or a passport of Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong or Taiwan? Then you have the nationality of a country for which a provisional residence permit (MVV) is required. This means you need an MVV.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Making an appointment at a Dutch representation", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You apply for the MVV and the residence permit at the same time at a Dutch representation in your country of origin. To do this, you must first make an appointment with the Dutch representation. You cannot make an appointment in your country of continuous residence. Check Netherlandsworldwide.nl for information about making an appointment.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "During the appointment, you will receive a confirmation of receipt and your V-number. You will also provide your biometric data. You give your fingerprints and your signature. These data are needed for the residence permit.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Sending the application to the IND", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Have you filled in the application form completely? And have you collected all required documents? Then send your application with the documents to the IND in the Netherlands. Do this within 3 weeks of the date that the Dutch representation filled in on the application form. The form states the where to send your application.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Japan and South Korea", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you have the nationality of Japan or South Korea? Then you do not need an MVV. However, you do need a pre-registration.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "What is pre-registration?", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "With a request for pre-registration, you inform the IND in advance that you want to apply for a Working Holiday. The IND will assess your request. Each year, a maximum of 200 Japanese and 200 South Koreans can receive a residence permit Working Holiday.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Pre-registrations for Japan temporarily not possible", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "At this moment, the maximum number of pre-registrations for Japan has been reached. If you have the Japanese nationality, you currently cannot make a request for pre-registration. We expect that you can make a request for pre-registration again after 1 April 2026.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Applying for pre-registration", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You must make a request for the pre-registration yourself. To do this, send an email to the IND. Include the following information in your email:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "your name", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "your date of birth", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "a copy of your passport.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Only with this data can we assess your pre-registration. After you have sent the email, you will receive a confirmation of receipt. Within 2 weeks, you will receive an email stating whether the pre-registration was successful.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Validity of the pre-registration", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The pre-registration is valid for 90 days. If you are unable to apply for your residence permit within those 90 days, and your pre-registration is no longer valid, you must make a request for a new pre-registration. This is only possible if you pre-registration is no longer valid.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Applying for the residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Has your pre-registration been successful? Then you can apply for the residence permit in the following 2 ways:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "With a written application form. You send the form by post.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "At an IND desk if you are in the Netherlands. Call the IND to make an appointment.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You cannot be older than 30 years old at the time the IND receives your application for a residence permit.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Australia, New Zealand and Canada", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you have the nationality of Australia, New Zealand, or Canada? Then you do not need an MVV. You also do not need a pre-registration. You can apply for the residence permit directly.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You can apply for the residence permit in the following 3 ways:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "With an online application form. Are you still abroad? Then submit your application no earlier than 90 days before you travel to the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "With a written application form. You send the form by post.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "At an IND desk if you are in the Netherlands. Call the IND to make an appointment.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "4. Pay for application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The application costs € 85,00. For all fees and exceptions, visit our website Fees: application costs.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong and Taiwan", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The application form explains how you pay the costs. Pay the costs within 3 weeks from the date the Dutch representation has written on your application form.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Australia, New Zealand, Canada, Japan and South Korea", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You will receive a letter explaining how to pay the costs.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "2. Wait for decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The IND must take a decision within 90 days. This is called the decision period.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "We can extend the decision period if it takes longer to decide. For example, because the application is not complete. In that case, the IND will send a message.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "5. Wait for decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The IND must take a decision within 90 days. This is called the decision period.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "We can extend the decision period if it takes longer to decide. For example, because the application is not complete. In that case, the IND will send a message.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "3. Decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You will receive a message with the decision. The decision will be positive or negative.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Positive decision: you will get an MVV and a residence permit.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Negative decision: you will not receive an MVV and residence permit. You can object against this decision.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "6. Decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You will receive the decision in a letter. The decision will be positive or negative.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Positive decision: you will get a residence permit.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Negative decision: you will not receive a residence permit. You can object against this decision.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "7. Making an appointment for an MVV visa sticker and collecting the residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Argentina,Uruguay, Hong Kong en Taiwan", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Have you received a positive decision? You can travel to the Netherlands with the MVV.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Making an appointment for an MVV sticker", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You will have to make an appointment at the Dutch representation. This is the embassy or consulate that you filled in on the application form. You have to make the appointment within 3 months after the IND has taken a decision on your application.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Your passport must be valid for at least another 6 months when the Dutch representation places the MVV visa sticker in the passport. The MVV is valid for 90 days.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Argentina, Australia, Canada, Hong Kong, Japan, New Zealand, Taiwan, Uruguay and South Korea", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Have you received a positive decision? And have you provided your biometric data? Then your residence permit is ready for collection at an IND desk. You must make an appointment to collect it. Make an appointment to collect your residence document.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Application forms", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Online application form Working Holiday", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You can only use the online application form if you have the nationality of Australia, Canada or New-Zealand. And you apply for a residence permit for the first time in the Netherlands.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Apply online", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Written application forms", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you have the nationality of Australia, Canada, New Zealand Japan or South Korea? And are you unable to submit the application online? Use the following written application form:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Application for the purpose of residence ''exchange'' within the context of the Working Holiday Program or Working Holiday Scheme 7520 (PDF, 506.6 KB)", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Do you have the nationality of Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong or a passport issued by Taiwan? Use the following written application form. This form is only available in English.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Application for admission and residence for a Working Holiday (Argentina, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Uruguay nationals) 9561 (PDF, 254.68 KB)", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "The residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Find out what else you need to know about the residence permit:", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Working with the residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "It says on the back of your residence permit: ‘Work permit not required for occasional work while on WHP/WHS, other work not permitted’ (in Dutch: TWV niet vereist voor incidentele arbeid in het kader van WHP/WHS, andere arbeid niet toegestaan).", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Occasional work means that you are allowed to work only to financially support your stay in the Netherlands. Then your employer does not need a work permit (in Dutch: tewerkstellingsvergunning or TWV) for you. You may, for example work fulltime, but not the whole year for the same employer. Nor may you work as a self-employed person. This is because the main purpose of your stay is cultural exchange.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Legal obligations", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You have an obligation to provide information. This means that you must notify the IND of changes in your situation.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Read more about your obligation to provide information.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "The IND checks whether you meet your obligations. If you do not, you may get an administrative fine.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Validity of the residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The residence permit for a working holiday is valid for a maximum of 1 year.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Type of residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The residence permit is type I, temporary regular residence permit.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Other applications", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You cannot extend the working holiday residence permit. Has your residence permit been damaged, lost or stolen? Then have your residence permit replaced. Visit the web page residence permit damaged or change of details or residence permit lost or stolen.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Living in the Netherlands", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Travel and return visa (TKV)", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Brochure", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Coming to the Netherlands for exchange 3088 (PDF, 608.33 KB)", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Who can apply for the residence permit?", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Requirements", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Process and costs", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Application forms", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "The residence permit", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "NarrativeText"}], "fetch_date": "2026-03-02"}', 'webpage', '2026-03-28 16:32:08.725204+00', '2026-03-28 16:25:32.781568+00', 'Residence permit Working Holiday

Last update: 9 February 2026

Working Holiday (WHP or WHS) is a cultural exchange programme for young people aged 18 to 30 from certain countries. The main purpose is to get to know Dutch society and culture. Read what the requirements are and how to apply for the residence permit.

Who can apply for the residence permit?

Requirements

Process and costs

Application forms

The residence permit

See also

Who can apply for the residence permit?

You can only apply for the residence permit if you have the nationality or a passport of 1 of the following countries or territories:

Argentina

Australia

Canada

Hong Kong

Japan

New Zealand

Taiwan

Uruguay

South Korea

Do you have another nationality? Then you cannot apply for a residence permit Working Holiday.

Maximum number of participants

Every year, a maximum of 100 young people per country from Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong and Taiwan can come to the Netherlands for a Working Holiday residence permit. And per country a maximum of 200 young people from Japan and South Korea.

Requirements

These requirements apply to you:

You have the nationality of a country with which you can apply for a Working Holiday residence permit. Check who can apply for the residence permit.

You meet the general requirements that apply to everyone.

You are at least 18 and no older than 30 years old at the time of the application.

You previously did not have a residence permit in the Netherlands for an exchange residence purpose.

You have a return ticket. Or you can show that you have enough money to buy a return ticket.

You have enough money during your stay in the Netherlands. You must estimate how much money you need. You may not receive social benefits from Dutch public funds.

You have insurance that covers the cost of healthcare in the Netherlands.

You are coming to the Netherlands for cultural exchange. The main purpose is to get to know Dutch society and culture. You may complete a short study or course during the exchange.

You meet the requirements set out in the Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) or the Note Verbale of your country. For example, you must live in the country of your nationality when you submit the application.

Japan and South Korea: extra requirement

Do you have the nationality of Japan or South Korea? Then you need to make a request for pre-registration. Read how to make a request for pre-registration in step 3 at Process and costs.

Process and costs

Show details Hide details

1. Check requirements

A valid provisional residence permit (MVV) is needed for this application

Make sure you meet the requirements.

1. Check requirements

Make sure you meet the requirements.

2. Collect documents

The written application form lists which documents you need. This form is only available in English. Collect all documents before you submit the application.

Have official foreign documents legalised and translated into Dutch, English, French or German.

Japan and South Korea: extra documents

Do you have the nationality of Japan or South Korea? Then you also need a valid proof of pre-registration. This is an email from the IND. Read how to apply for the pre-registration in step 3.

3. Apply

The application process depends on your nationality. Choose the country of your nationality and find out how to apply.

Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong and Taiwan

Japan and South Korea

Australia, New Zealand and Canada

Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong and Taiwan

Do you have the nationality or a passport of Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong or Taiwan? Then you have the nationality of a country for which a provisional residence permit (MVV) is required. This means you need an MVV.

Making an appointment at a Dutch representation

You apply for the MVV and the residence permit at the same time at a Dutch representation in your country of origin. To do this, you must first make an appointment with the Dutch representation. You cannot make an appointment in your country of continuous residence. Check Netherlandsworldwide.nl for information about making an appointment.

During the appointment, you will receive a confirmation of receipt and your V-number. You will also provide your biometric data. You give your fingerprints and your signature. These data are needed for the residence permit.

Sending the application to the IND

Have you filled in the application form completely? And have you collected all required documents? Then send your application with the documents to the IND in the Netherlands. Do this within 3 weeks of the date that the Dutch representation filled in on the application form. The form states the where to send your application.

Japan and South Korea

Do you have the nationality of Japan or South Korea? Then you do not need an MVV. However, you do need a pre-registration.

What is pre-registration?

With a request for pre-registration, you inform the IND in advance that you want to apply for a Working Holiday. The IND will assess your request. Each year, a maximum of 200 Japanese and 200 South Koreans can receive a residence permit Working Holiday.

Pre-registrations for Japan temporarily not possible

At this moment, the maximum number of pre-registrations for Japan has been reached. If you have the Japanese nationality, you currently cannot make a request for pre-registration. We expect that you can make a request for pre-registration again after 1 April 2026.

Applying for pre-registration

You must make a request for the pre-registration yourself. To do this, send an email to the IND. Include the following information in your email:

your name

your date of birth

a copy of your passport.

Only with this data can we assess your pre-registration. After you have sent the email, you will receive a confirmation of receipt. Within 2 weeks, you will receive an email stating whether the pre-registration was successful.

Validity of the pre-registration

The pre-registration is valid for 90 days. If you are unable to apply for your residence permit within those 90 days, and your pre-registration is no longer valid, you must make a request for a new pre-registration. This is only possible if you pre-registration is no longer valid.

Applying for the residence permit

Has your pre-registration been successful? Then you can apply for the residence permit in the following 2 ways:

With a written application form. You send the form by post.

At an IND desk if you are in the Netherlands. Call the IND to make an appointment.

You cannot be older than 30 years old at the time the IND receives your application for a residence permit.

Australia, New Zealand and Canada

Do you have the nationality of Australia, New Zealand, or Canada? Then you do not need an MVV. You also do not need a pre-registration. You can apply for the residence permit directly.

You can apply for the residence permit in the following 3 ways:

With an online application form. Are you still abroad? Then submit your application no earlier than 90 days before you travel to the Netherlands.

With a written application form. You send the form by post.

At an IND desk if you are in the Netherlands. Call the IND to make an appointment.

4. Pay for application

The application costs € 85,00. For all fees and exceptions, visit our website Fees: application costs.

Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong and Taiwan

The application form explains how you pay the costs. Pay the costs within 3 weeks from the date the Dutch representation has written on your application form.

Australia, New Zealand, Canada, Japan and South Korea

You will receive a letter explaining how to pay the costs.

2. Wait for decision on application

The IND must take a decision within 90 days. This is called the decision period.

We can extend the decision period if it takes longer to decide. For example, because the application is not complete. In that case, the IND will send a message.

5. Wait for decision on application

The IND must take a decision within 90 days. This is called the decision period.

We can extend the decision period if it takes longer to decide. For example, because the application is not complete. In that case, the IND will send a message.

3. Decision on application

You will receive a message with the decision. The decision will be positive or negative.

Positive decision: you will get an MVV and a residence permit.

Negative decision: you will not receive an MVV and residence permit. You can object against this decision.

6. Decision on application

You will receive the decision in a letter. The decision will be positive or negative.

Positive decision: you will get a residence permit.

Negative decision: you will not receive a residence permit. You can object against this decision.

7. Making an appointment for an MVV visa sticker and collecting the residence permit

Argentina,Uruguay, Hong Kong en Taiwan

Have you received a positive decision? You can travel to the Netherlands with the MVV.

Making an appointment for an MVV sticker

You will have to make an appointment at the Dutch representation. This is the embassy or consulate that you filled in on the application form. You have to make the appointment within 3 months after the IND has taken a decision on your application.

Your passport must be valid for at least another 6 months when the Dutch representation places the MVV visa sticker in the passport. The MVV is valid for 90 days.

Argentina, Australia, Canada, Hong Kong, Japan, New Zealand, Taiwan, Uruguay and South Korea

Have you received a positive decision? And have you provided your biometric data? Then your residence permit is ready for collection at an IND desk. You must make an appointment to collect it. Make an appointment to collect your residence document.

Application forms

Online application form Working Holiday

You can only use the online application form if you have the nationality of Australia, Canada or New-Zealand. And you apply for a residence permit for the first time in the Netherlands.

Apply online

Written application forms

Do you have the nationality of Australia, Canada, New Zealand Japan or South Korea? And are you unable to submit the application online? Use the following written application form:

Application for the purpose of residence ''exchange'' within the context of the Working Holiday Program or Working Holiday Scheme 7520 (PDF, 506.6 KB)

Do you have the nationality of Argentina, Uruguay, Hong Kong or a passport issued by Taiwan? Use the following written application form. This form is only available in English.

Application for admission and residence for a Working Holiday (Argentina, Hong Kong, Taiwan, Uruguay nationals) 9561 (PDF, 254.68 KB)

The residence permit

Find out what else you need to know about the residence permit:

Working with the residence permit

It says on the back of your residence permit: ‘Work permit not required for occasional work while on WHP/WHS, other work not permitted’ (in Dutch: TWV niet vereist voor incidentele arbeid in het kader van WHP/WHS, andere arbeid niet toegestaan).

Occasional work means that you are allowed to work only to financially support your stay in the Netherlands. Then your employer does not need a work permit (in Dutch: tewerkstellingsvergunning or TWV) for you. You may, for example work fulltime, but not the whole year for the same employer. Nor may you work as a self-employed person. This is because the main purpose of your stay is cultural exchange.

Legal obligations

You have an obligation to provide information. This means that you must notify the IND of changes in your situation.

Read more about your obligation to provide information.

The IND checks whether you meet your obligations. If you do not, you may get an administrative fine.

Validity of the residence permit

The residence permit for a working holiday is valid for a maximum of 1 year.

Type of residence permit

The residence permit is type I, temporary regular residence permit.

Other applications

You cannot extend the working holiday residence permit. Has your residence permit been damaged, lost or stolen? Then have your residence permit replaced. Visit the web page residence permit damaged or change of details or residence permit lost or stolen.

See also

Living in the Netherlands

Travel and return visa (TKV)

Brochure

Coming to the Netherlands for exchange 3088 (PDF, 608.33 KB)

Who can apply for the residence permit?

Requirements

Process and costs

