	('adaeb0a6-b376-4591-b3a4-2ab4f89513de', 'Staying in the Netherlands if you no longer live with an EU citizen', 'https://ind.nl/en/replace-extend-renew-and-change/change/staying-in-the-netherlands-if-you-no-longer-live-with-an-eu-citizen', '{"category": "replace-extend-renew-and-change/change", "elements": [{"text": "Staying in the Netherlands if you no longer live with an EU citizen", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Last update: 8 July 2025", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "You had the right of residence in the Netherlands under EU law because you lived with a family member or partner from the EU, EEA or Switzerland. You no longer live together. For example because your family member or partner died or your relationship has ended. Find out if you are allowed to continue to live in the Netherlands.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Situations in which you may continue to live in the Netherlands", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Apply for a new residence document", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Inform the IND when no longer living together", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Situations in which you may continue to live in the Netherlands", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you no longer live with your family member or partner from the EU, EEA or Switzerland? Then you can stay in the Netherlands in some situations. From now on, we will call your family member or partner a citizen of the Union.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You have EU, EEA or Swiss nationality", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Then you can continue to live in the Netherlands. However, there are requirements. Find out what the requirements are on the page Living in the Netherlands as an EU, EEA or Swiss citizen.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You have another nationality", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You have another nationality and no longer live with the citizen of the Union. Select your situation below and find out whether you can continue to stay in the Netherlands. Is the citizen of the Union a Dutch national? Then the situations only apply to you if the Dutch national has made use of EU law. Find out when EU law applies to Dutch nationals.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Show details Hide details", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You have been in the Netherlands for 5 years or longer", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You may have permanent residency. Find out more on the page Permanent residence permit for Union citizens and their family.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Union citizen has died", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You had been living with the citizen of the Union in the Netherlands for at least 1 year at the time of death. Then you can continue to live in the Netherlands.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You are the child of the citizen of the Union who has left or died", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You are studying in the Netherlands. You and the parent caring for you are allowed to stay in the Netherlands until you complete your study programme.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Marriage or relationship with the citizen of the Union has ended", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Has your marriage or relationship with the citizen of the Union ended? Then you are allowed to continue to live in the Netherlands in these situations:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Your marriage or relationship lasted at least 3 years at the start of the divorce or ending of the relationship. And you lived at least 1 year of the marriage or relationship in the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have been awarded custody of the (minor) children. Or you have parental access rights and the judge has ordered that you must be able to see your children in the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "There is a special or difficult situation. For example, you were the victim of domestic violence during your marriage or relationship. Or you are the victim of honour-based violence.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your income is high enough (income requirement)", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "You must have enough income to be allowed to continue to live in the Netherlands. We call this the income requirement. For the income requirement, it does not matter which nationality you have. In these situations, your income is high enough:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You are an employee or entrepreneur. You carry out genuine and effective work. This means that you work at least 40% of the regular full working week. Or you earn at least 50% of the social assistance benefit applicable to you.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have an income that is the same or higher than the standard amount applicable to your family situation. And you have health insurance in the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Apply for a new residence document", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you no longer live with the citizen of the Union and are you allowed to continue to live in the Netherlands? Then you sometimes need a new residence document. Look at the following situations and check whether you must apply for a new residence document:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Your residence document is still valid. You will keep this document and do not need to apply for a new one. However, you must notify the IND that the situation has changed.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your residence document is no longer valid. And you do not have permanent residency yet. You must apply for a new residence document. Find out more on the page Verification against EU law for Union citizen family members.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have been living in the Netherlands continuously for 5 years. You may have permanent residency. You must apply for a new residence document. Find out more on the page Permanent residence permit for Union citizens and their family.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Inform the IND when no longer living together", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you no longer live together with the citizen of the Union? Then inform us. You can use this using this form:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Reporting form for foreign nationals 7597 (PDF, 216.2 KB)", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Permanent residence permit for Union citizens and their family", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Verification against EU law for Union citizen family members", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Rules and regulations", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Article 8.14 Aliens Decree (Vreemdelingenbesluit 2000)", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Article 8.15 Aliens Decree (Vreemdelingenbesluit 2000)​", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Articles 12 and 13 Directive 2004/38/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Situations in which you may continue to live in the Netherlands", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Apply for a new residence document", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Inform the IND when no longer living together", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "See also", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Your Europe", "type": "Image"}], "fetch_date": "2026-03-02"}', 'webpage', '2026-03-28 16:32:08.725204+00', '2026-03-28 16:25:32.781568+00', 'Staying in the Netherlands if you no longer live with an EU citizen

Last update: 8 July 2025

You had the right of residence in the Netherlands under EU law because you lived with a family member or partner from the EU, EEA or Switzerland. You no longer live together. For example because your family member or partner died or your relationship has ended. Find out if you are allowed to continue to live in the Netherlands.

Situations in which you may continue to live in the Netherlands

Apply for a new residence document

Inform the IND when no longer living together

See also

Situations in which you may continue to live in the Netherlands

Do you no longer live with your family member or partner from the EU, EEA or Switzerland? Then you can stay in the Netherlands in some situations. From now on, we will call your family member or partner a citizen of the Union.

You have EU, EEA or Swiss nationality

Then you can continue to live in the Netherlands. However, there are requirements. Find out what the requirements are on the page Living in the Netherlands as an EU, EEA or Swiss citizen.

You have another nationality

You have another nationality and no longer live with the citizen of the Union. Select your situation below and find out whether you can continue to stay in the Netherlands. Is the citizen of the Union a Dutch national? Then the situations only apply to you if the Dutch national has made use of EU law. Find out when EU law applies to Dutch nationals.

Show details Hide details

You have been in the Netherlands for 5 years or longer

You may have permanent residency. Find out more on the page Permanent residence permit for Union citizens and their family.

Union citizen has died

You had been living with the citizen of the Union in the Netherlands for at least 1 year at the time of death. Then you can continue to live in the Netherlands.

You are the child of the citizen of the Union who has left or died

You are studying in the Netherlands. You and the parent caring for you are allowed to stay in the Netherlands until you complete your study programme.

Marriage or relationship with the citizen of the Union has ended

Has your marriage or relationship with the citizen of the Union ended? Then you are allowed to continue to live in the Netherlands in these situations:

Your marriage or relationship lasted at least 3 years at the start of the divorce or ending of the relationship. And you lived at least 1 year of the marriage or relationship in the Netherlands.

You have been awarded custody of the (minor) children. Or you have parental access rights and the judge has ordered that you must be able to see your children in the Netherlands.

There is a special or difficult situation. For example, you were the victim of domestic violence during your marriage or relationship. Or you are the victim of honour-based violence.

Your income is high enough (income requirement)

You must have enough income to be allowed to continue to live in the Netherlands. We call this the income requirement. For the income requirement, it does not matter which nationality you have. In these situations, your income is high enough:

You are an employee or entrepreneur. You carry out genuine and effective work. This means that you work at least 40% of the regular full working week. Or you earn at least 50% of the social assistance benefit applicable to you.

You have an income that is the same or higher than the standard amount applicable to your family situation. And you have health insurance in the Netherlands.

Apply for a new residence document

Do you no longer live with the citizen of the Union and are you allowed to continue to live in the Netherlands? Then you sometimes need a new residence document. Look at the following situations and check whether you must apply for a new residence document:

Your residence document is still valid. You will keep this document and do not need to apply for a new one. However, you must notify the IND that the situation has changed.

Your residence document is no longer valid. And you do not have permanent residency yet. You must apply for a new residence document. Find out more on the page Verification against EU law for Union citizen family members.

You have been living in the Netherlands continuously for 5 years. You may have permanent residency. You must apply for a new residence document. Find out more on the page Permanent residence permit for Union citizens and their family.

Inform the IND when no longer living together

Do you no longer live together with the citizen of the Union? Then inform us. You can use this using this form:

Reporting form for foreign nationals 7597 (PDF, 216.2 KB)

See also

Permanent residence permit for Union citizens and their family

Verification against EU law for Union citizen family members

Rules and regulations

Article 8.14 Aliens Decree (Vreemdelingenbesluit 2000)

Article 8.15 Aliens Decree (Vreemdelingenbesluit 2000)​

Articles 12 and 13 Directive 2004/38/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council

