ype W2 document", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "These are the cases in which you can apply for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W2 yourself:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You have been granted postponement of departure because you are ill and cannot travel.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You are the victim of human trafficking or reporting as a witness of human trafficking.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have applied for asylum before. Now you have applied for a residence permit for a different reason. For example, for medical treatment or because you are unable to leave the Netherlands through no fault of your own.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Your application for an asylum residence permit has not been processed. This is because under the Dublin Regulation another Member State is responsible for processing your application. You are waiting for transfer to that other Member State.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "The European Court of Human Rights (ECtHR) has taken a provisional measure under Rule 39 of the procedural rules of the ECtHR, and the State of the Netherlands has requested suspension of removal.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Requirements application Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W2", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "These are the requirements you must meet for the Type W2 document:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You do not have a valid passport.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You are allowed to wait for your application in the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You do not receive any money from the Dutch government to live and reside in the Netherlands.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Costs of a Foreign Nationals Identity Card", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The application for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document is free of charge.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Application forms", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "In these situations you can apply for the Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W online:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "You have applied for extension of your asylum residence permit and are still waiting for a decision.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "You have applied for a permanent asylum residence permit and you are still waiting for a decision.", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "To apply online you need DigiD with SMS verification and internet banking (iDEAL).", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Start online application", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Written form", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Are you unable to apply for the Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W online? Or do you want to apply for Type W2? You can send the following form by post:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Application replacement or renewal of a foreign nationals document 6013 (PDF, 270.98 KB)", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Wait for decision on application", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "The IND will take a decision within 8 weeks on the application for the Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W or W2. This is called the decision period.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Foreign Nationals Identity Document lost, stolen, damaged or incorrect personal details", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Has your Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W or W2 been lost, stolen or damaged? Or are the personal details on the document incorrect? Then you can apply for a new Foreign Nationals Identity Document. For more information, visit Residence permit lost or stolen or Residence permit damaged or change of personal details.", "type": "NarrativeText"}], "fetch_date": "2026-03-02"}', 'webpage', '2026-03-28 16:32:08.725204+00', '2026-03-28 16:25:32.781568+00', 'Foreign Nationals Identity Document (Type W and Type W2)

Last update: 28 October 2025

You need a Foreign Nationals Identity Document (in Dutch: Vreemdelingen Identiteitsbewijs or VI). Find out when you will get a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W or Type W2 and when you can apply for it yourself.

The Foreign Nationals Identity Document

Foreign Nationals Identity Document: Type W document

Foreign Nationals Identity Document: Type W2 document

Costs of a Foreign Nationals Identity Card

Application forms

Foreign Nationals Identity Document lost, stolen, damaged or incorrect personal details

The Foreign Nationals Identity Document

A Foreign Nationals Identity Document (VI) is a valid proof of identity. It is not a residence permit. This means that you cannot travel abroad with it.

The following information is mentioned on a Foreign Nationals Identity Document:

Who you are and what nationality you have.

That you are allowed to be in the Netherlands. You are allowed to be in the Netherlands because you have submitted an application for a residence permit. Or because you have submitted a different application to be allowed to stay temporarily in the Netherlands. And you are still waiting for a decision.

See what a Foreign Nationals Identity Document looks like.

Foreign Nationals Identity Document: Type W document

These are the situations in which you can get or apply for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W:

You have applied for asylum for the first time. You will automatically get a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W. You do not have to apply for this yourself.

You have applied for extension of your temporary asylum residence permit. You are still waiting for a decision. You can apply for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W yourself.

You have applied for a permanent asylum residence permit and you are still waiting for a decision. You can apply for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W yourself.

You have appealed against the rejection of your asylum application (temporary or permanent). Or you have appealed against the rejection of the extension of your asylum residence permit. You are still waiting for a decision by the court. You can apply for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W yourself.

You have applied for replacement of your residence permit (temporary or permanent). You are replacing your residence permit because it has been damaged, lost or stolen. Or because your personal details on the residence permit are not correct. You can apply for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W yourself.

You have applied for asylum. Or you have applied for extension of your temporary asylum residence permit or permanent asylum residence permit. You are still waiting for a decision and your current document type W is about to expire or has expired. You can apply for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W yourself.

Foreign Nationals Identity Document: Type W2 document

These are the cases in which you can apply for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W2 yourself:

You have been granted postponement of departure because you are ill and cannot travel.

You are the victim of human trafficking or reporting as a witness of human trafficking.

You have applied for asylum before. Now you have applied for a residence permit for a different reason. For example, for medical treatment or because you are unable to leave the Netherlands through no fault of your own.

Your application for an asylum residence permit has not been processed. This is because under the Dublin Regulation another Member State is responsible for processing your application. You are waiting for transfer to that other Member State.

The European Court of Human Rights (ECtHR) has taken a provisional measure under Rule 39 of the procedural rules of the ECtHR, and the State of the Netherlands has requested suspension of removal.

Requirements application Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W2

These are the requirements you must meet for the Type W2 document:

You do not have a valid passport.

You are allowed to wait for your application in the Netherlands.

You do not receive any money from the Dutch government to live and reside in the Netherlands.

Costs of a Foreign Nationals Identity Card

The application for a Foreign Nationals Identity Document is free of charge.

Application forms

In these situations you can apply for the Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W online:

You have applied for extension of your asylum residence permit and are still waiting for a decision.

You have applied for a permanent asylum residence permit and you are still waiting for a decision.

To apply online you need DigiD with SMS verification and internet banking (iDEAL).

Start online application

Written form

Are you unable to apply for the Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W online? Or do you want to apply for Type W2? You can send the following form by post:

Application replacement or renewal of a foreign nationals document 6013 (PDF, 270.98 KB)

Wait for decision on application

The IND will take a decision within 8 weeks on the application for the Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W or W2. This is called the decision period.

Foreign Nationals Identity Document lost, stolen, damaged or incorrect personal details

Has your Foreign Nationals Identity Document Type W or W2 been lost, stolen or damaged? Or are the personal details on the document incorrect? Then you can apply for a new Foreign Nationals Identity Document. For more information, visit Residence permit lost or stolen or Residence permit damaged or change of personal details.'),
	('4d292b2a-5169-4e9d-812a-6d49079f89c2', 'Living in the Netherlands with a residence permit', 'https://ind.nl/en/living-in-the-netherlands-with-a-residence-permit', '{"category": "living-in-the-netherlands-with-a-residence-permit", "elements": [{"text": "Living in the Netherlands with a residence permit", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Read what else you need to arrange if you have received a Dutch residence permit. Or if your residence permit has been lost, stolen or damaged.", "type": "NarrativeText"}], "fetch_date": "2026-03-02"}', 'webpage', '2026-03-28 16:32:08.725204+00', '2026-03-28 16:25:32.781568+00', 'Living in the Netherlands with a residence permit

Read what else you need to arrange if you have received a Dutch residence permit. Or if your residence permit has been lost, stolen or damaged.'),
	('8a83dfe2-450e-466b-83da-453f41950d06', 'Living in the Netherlands', 'https://ind.nl/en/living-in-the-netherlands-with-a-residence-permit/living-in-the-netherlands', '{"category": "living-in-the-netherlands-with-a-residence-permit", "elements": [{"text": "Living in the Netherlands", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Last update: 29 February 2024", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "You recently came to live in the Netherlands. You have some important matters to arrange after arrival. Find out what you have to do and what your obligations are.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Registration with municipality", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "TB test", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Register for healthcare insurance", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "School attendance for children", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Civic integration in the Netherlands", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "The Netherlands as your main residence", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Legal obligations", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Leaving the Netherlands", "type": "ListItem"}, {"text": "Registration with municipality", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Are you coming to live in the Netherlands for more than 4 months? Then you have to register with the municipality in the Personal Records Database (in Dutch: Basisregistratie Personen or BRP). This applies to everyone. After this registration, the municipality will issue a Citizen Service Number for you (in Dutch: Burgerservicenummer or BSN). Go to Rijksoverheid.nl for more information on the BRP.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Legalised and translated birth certificate", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "A legalised and translated birth certificate is necessary to register with the municipality. Bring your birth certificate with you to the Netherlands. Ask the municipality which other documents are needed for registration. Find out more about the translation and legalisation of documents.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "TB test", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Have you indicated in the application that you will take a TB (tuberculosis) test? Then make an appointment at the public health service (in Dutch: Gemeentelijke Gezondheidsdienst or GGD). Do this within 3 months after you have received your residence permit. Take with you to the appointment:", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Appendix TB test referral form 7604(PDF, 219.94 KB)", "type": "UncategorizedText"}, {"text": "Register for healthcare insurance", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Everyone who lives in the Netherlands must register for healthcare insurance. Do this within 4 months after your arrival in the Netherlands. Go to Rijksoverheid.nl for more information on healthcare insurance.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Residence permit for study, Working Holiday (WHP/WHS) or cultural exchange", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you have a residence permit for study, Working Holiday (WHS/WHP) or cultural exchange? Then your foreign healthcare insurance is enough if it includes the Netherlands. Do you have a residence permit for study, WHS/WHP or cultural exchange but you will work in the Netherlands? Then you have to register for Dutch healthcare insurance.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "School attendance for children", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "In the Netherlands, children from 5 to 16 years have to complete compulsory education. This means that they must go to school. Does this apply to your child? Then register the child at a school. Go to Rijksoverheid.nl for more information on the obligation to attend school.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Civic integration in the Netherlands", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Did you get a residence permit? In certain situations, you are required to learn the Dutch language and to learn about Dutch society and its labour market. This is called civic integration. Not everyone is required to integrate. Go to Rijksoverheid.nl for more information about civic integration.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Civic integration if applying for permanent residence permit or naturalisation", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you want to become a Dutch citizen via naturalisation? Or are you going to apply for a permanent residence permit or a residence permit on ‘humanitarian non-temporary grounds after residing with a family member or relative for 5 years''? Then you must prove that you are civically integrated. Even if you were not initially required to take the civic integration examination. Read more about the civic integration examination as a requirement for a different residence permit or naturalisation.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "The Netherlands as your main residence", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "If you have a Dutch residence permit, your main residence must be in the Netherlands. This means that you live in the Netherlands and spend most of your time here. Will you go abroad for a longer period of time? Then the IND can decide to withdraw or to not extend your residence permit. Read more about main residence in the Netherlands.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Legal obligations", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Do you have a residence permit? Read more about a foreign national’s obligation to provide information.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Legal sponsor’s obligations", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Is someone coming to live with you in the Netherlands? Then you are their sponsor. A sponsor has an obligation to provide information and an obligation to keep and maintain records. If you are a recognised sponsor then you also have a duty of care. Read more about the legal sponsor´s obligations on the page Obligations of sponsor and recognised sponsor. And on the page Obligations foreign national and sponsor of family member.", "type": "NarrativeText"}, {"text": "Leaving the Netherlands", "type": "Title"}, {"text": "Are you permanently leaving the Netherlands? Then you need to arrange certain matters before you leave. Read more about Leaving the Netherlands.", "type": "NarrativeText"}], "fetch_date": "2026-03-02"}', 'webpage', '2026-03-28 16:32:08.725204+00', '2026-03-28 16:25:32.781568+00', 'Living in the Netherlands

Last update: 29 February 2024

You recently came to live in the Netherlands. You have some important matters to arrange after arrival. Find out what you have to do and what your obligations are.

Registration with municipality

TB test

Register for healthcare insurance

School attendance for children

Civic integration in the Netherlands

The Netherlands as your main residence

Legal obligations

Leaving the Netherlands

Registration with municipality

Are you coming to live in the Netherlands for more than 4 months? Then you have to register with the municipality in the Personal Records Database (in Dutch: Basisregistratie Personen or BRP). This applies to everyone. After this registration, the municipality will issue a Citizen Service Number for you (in Dutch: Burgerservicenummer or BSN). Go to Rijksoverheid.nl for more information on the BRP.

Legalised and translated birth certificate

A legalised and translated birth certificate is necessary to register with the municipality. Bring your birth certificate with you to the Netherlands. Ask the municipality which other documents are needed for registration. Find out more about the translation and legalisation of documents.

TB test

Have you indicated in the application that you will take a TB (tuberculosis) test? Then make an appointment at the public health service (in Dutch: Gemeentelijke Gezondheidsdienst or GGD). Do this within 3 months after you have received your residence permit. Take with you to the appointment:

Appendix TB test referral form 7604(PDF, 219.94 KB)

Register for healthcare insurance

Everyone who lives in the Netherlands must register for healthcare insurance. Do this within 4 months after your arrival in the Netherlands. Go to Rijksoverheid.nl for more information on healthcare insurance.

Residence permit for study, Working Holiday (WHP/WHS) or cultural exchange

Do you have a residence permit for study, Working Holiday (WHS/WHP) or cultural exchange? Then your foreign healthcare insurance is enough if it includes the Netherlands. Do you have a residence permit for study, WHS/WHP or cultural exchange but you will work in the Netherlands? Then you have to register for Dutch healthcare insurance.

School attendance for children

In the Netherlands, children from 5 to 16 years have to complete compulsory education. This means that they must go to school. Does this apply to your child? Then register the child at a school. Go to Rijksoverheid.nl for more information on the obligation to attend school.

Civic integration in the Netherlands

Did you get a residence permit? In certain situations, you are required to learn the Dutch language and to learn about Dutch society and its labour market. This is called civic integration. Not everyone is required to integrate. Go to Rijksoverheid.nl for more information about civic integration.

Civic integration if applying for permanent residence permit or naturalisation

Do you want to become a Dutch citizen via naturalisation? Or are you going to apply for a permanent residence permit or a residence permit on ‘humanitarian non-temporary grounds after residing with a family member or relative for 5 years''? Then you must prove that you are civically integrated. Even if you were not initially required to take the civic integration examination. Read more about the civic integration examination as a requirement for a different residence permit or naturalisation.

The Netherlands as your main residence

If you have a Dutch residence permit, your main residence must be in the Netherlands. This means that you live in the Netherlands and spend most of your time here. Will you go abroad for a longer period of time? Then the IND can decide to withdraw or to not extend your residence permit. Read more about main residence in the Netherlands.

Legal obligations

Do you have a residence permit? Read more about a foreign national’s obligation to provide information.

Legal sponsor’s obligations

Is someone coming to live with you in the Netherlands? Then you are their sponsor. A sponsor has an obligation to provide information and an obligation to keep and maintain records. If you are a recognised sponsor then you also have a duty of care. Read more about the legal sponsor´s obligations on the page Obligations of sponsor and recognised sponsor. And on the page Obligations foreign national and sponsor of family member.

Leaving the Netherlands

Are you permanently leaving the Netherlands? Then you need to arrange certain matters before you leave. Read more about Leaving the Netherlands.'),
